DOCUMENT();

loadMacros(
  "PGstandard.pl",
  "MathObjects.pl",
  "AnswerFormatHelp.pl",
  "PGcourse.pl"
);

TEXT(beginproblem());

Context("Numeric");

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

$h = random(-7,7,2);
$k = random(2,8,2);
$y = random(-8,2,2);
# if y = k, we have a line, not a quadratic
$y = $k + 1 if ( $y == $k );

$top = $y-$k;
$bot = $h**2;
$a_disp = "$top/$bot";
$a_math = "\frac{$top}{$bot}";
$ans = "($a_disp) (x-$h)^2+$k";

Context()->texStrings;
BEGIN_TEXT
Find a formula for the quadratic function whose graph has its vertex at \( ($h,$k) \) and its \(y\)-intercept at \( y = $y\).
$PAR
\( f(x) = \) \{ ans_rule(30) \}
\{ AnswerFormatHelp("formulas") \}
END_TEXT
Context()->normalStrings;

ANS(Compute("$ans")->cmp() );

#ANS(fun_cmp( $ans,vars=>'x') );

Context()->texStrings;
SOLUTION(EV3(<<'END_SOLUTION'));
$PAR
$BBOLD  SOLUTION $EBOLD
$PAR
Since the vertex is ($h, $k), we use the form \(y=a(x-h)^2+k \), with
\( h=$h \) and \( k=$k \).  We solve for \( a \) , substituting in the second point, (0, $y).
\[\begin{aligned}
 y &= a(x-$h)^2 + $k \\
 $y &= a(0-$h)^2+ $k \\
 $top &= $bot a \\
 $a_math &= a
\end{aligned}\]

Thus, an equation for the parabola is \( y = $a_math (x-$h)^2+$k \).

END_SOLUTION
Context()->normalStrings;

;
ENDDOCUMENT();
